<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-521-316  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 521 316.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  August 14 1989 v23 n33 p85(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Automation for the job search. (career-planning software)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Nash, Kim S.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Several software packages are available which automate the processof career planning and job hunting.andP;  New York career-counselingfirm Crystal-Barkley Corp has developed Career Design, a $125program which assists job hunters in self-assessment.andP;  Its menuhas three selections, 'Who Am I?,' 'What Do I Want?' and 'How Do IGet There?', which generate more than 50 question-and-answermodules.andP;  The program guides the user through exercises inidentifying likes, dislikes and personal goals as well aspractical skill assessment.andP;  Drake Beam Morin Inc's $129 CareerNavigator program is similarly constructed, but offers less userinteraction and has many modules with simple lists of basic tips.andO;Jamenair Ltd's $260 Super Job Search includes databases ofemployers and executive recruiters, helping users assemble contactlists and track their job search.andP;  Several packages for designingresumes are also available.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   Career Design (Computer program) (usage)Super Job Search (computer program) (usage)Career Navigator (Computer program) (usage).andO;Topic:     Career developmentJob SearchSoftware PackagesPlanning ApplicationsGoals and Objectives.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>